i as supreme authority (Mn_2.10, Mn_2.13) grounds itself on the heard-ness of the Veda. The transmission frame — 'Let it be heard' (Mn_1.4, Mn_1.60) — positions the text in the auditory register. No other mode of reception (reading, reasoning, writing) can create śruti; only hearing in an unbroken oral lineage authorizes the text as revealed.\n\nCynewulf's passage is the most dramatically rendered auditory event — 'his voice a balm' gives the heavenly voice physical, curative qualities — but the revelation doubles as a visual/inscriptional sign (the cross with written words). Iqbal's wahy opens with 'A Voice came' but closes with the Tablet and Pen, and Islamic theology already recognizes non-auditory modes of wahy. Only śruti collapses its entire authority onto a single modality: sound received by hearing.",
